    <div class="example" id="sync-atomic">
      <h2><a href="./">Go Assembly by Example</a>: Sync Atomic</h2>
      
      <table>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            <p>This example is taken from the <a href="https://golang.org/pkg/sync/atomic/">sync/atomic</a> package which provides low-level atomic memory primitives.
The swap operation, implemented by the SwapT functions, is the atomic equivalent of //    1. old = *addr
2.  *addr = new
3. return old</p>

          </td>
          <td class="code empty leading">
	        
            
          </td>
        </tr>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            
          </td>
          <td class="code leading">
	        
            <div class="highlight"><pre><span class="kn">package</span> <span class="nx">atomic</span>
</pre></div>

          </td>
        </tr>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            
          </td>
          <td class="code leading">
	        
            <div class="highlight"><pre><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="p">(</span>
    <span class="s">&quot;unsafe&quot;</span>
<span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

          </td>
        </tr>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            <p>SwapInt32 atomically stores new into *addr and returns the previous *addr value.</p>

          </td>
          <td class="code">
	        
            <div class="highlight"><pre><span class="kd">func</span> <span class="nx">SwapInt32</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nx">addr</span> <span class="o">*</span><span class="kt">int32</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="nx">new</span> <span class="kt">int32</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="nx">old</span> <span class="kt">int32</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

          </td>
        </tr>
        
      </table>
      
      <table>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            
          </td>
          <td class="code leading">
	        
            <div class="highlight"><pre><span class="gp">#</span>include <span class="s2">&quot;textflag.h&quot;</span>
</pre></div>

          </td>
        </tr>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            
          </td>
          <td class="code leading">
	        
            <div class="highlight"><pre><span class="go">TEXT ·SwapInt32(SB),NOSPLIT,$0-20</span>
<span class="go">	JMP	·SwapUint32(SB)</span>
</pre></div>

          </td>
        </tr>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            
          </td>
          <td class="code leading">
	        
            <div class="highlight"><pre><span class="go">TEXT ·SwapUint32(SB),NOSPLIT,$0-20</span>
<span class="go">	MOVQ	addr+0(FP), BP</span>
<span class="go">	MOVL	new+8(FP), AX</span>
</pre></div>

          </td>
        </tr>
        
        <tr>
          <td class="docs">
            <p>The <code>XCHGL</code> instruction is not vulnerable to a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hazard_(computer_architecture)#Write_after_read_.28WAR.29">Write-After-Read</a> as the bus is locked for the duration of the exchange.</p>

          </td>
          <td class="code">
	        
            <div class="highlight"><pre><span class="go">	XCHGL	AX, 0(BP)</span>
<span class="go">	MOVL	AX, old+16(FP)</span>
<span class="go">	RET</span>
</pre></div>

          </td>
        </tr>
        
      </table>
      
      
